  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Potable Water and Irrigation</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Local farmers</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The population of Los Cacaos doubled to 16,000 people after the earthquake because it was a transit point to the Dominican Republic and other Haitian border towns. The area suffered from deforestation and drought making farm yields very low. People contracted cholera from the local drinking water and the disease claimed almost 30 lives. JRS partnered with Dominican Sister Maria Marciano, a trained engineer and surveyor, to construct a water system  to provide clean drinking water and irrigation. The project has benefited approximately 2,000 people in Los Cacaos who now have access to clean water. Now, local farmers can earn a living thanks to irrigated fields, and they are improving the local ecology by planting trees. The successful completion of the project means the community is ready for a long-term education program. Los Cacaos has become a model to replicate for future endeavors.  

After success in Los Cacaos, JRS expanded into the nearby community of Tiroli. Similar to Los Cacaos, Tiroli experienced a 60% increase in its population following the earthquake because the village was a transit point for people migrating to the Dominican Republic. Working again with the Dominican Sisters, the project will construct a water system that will provide the community with clean water for drinking and irrigation. The beneficiaries include approximately 20,000 people that will have access to clean water and irrigation systems that will allow local peasants to earn a living.</narrative>
  </description>
